  "prompt": "What are the best books for C# for the beginner, intermediate, and advanced levels?",
  "response": "Here are some recommended books for different skill levels in C#:\n\nBeginner Level:\n1. \"C# Programming Yellow Book\" by Rob Miles (Free PDF)\n2. \"Head First C#\" by Andrew Stellman and Jennifer Greene\n3. \"C# 10 in a Nutshell\" by Joseph Albahari (beginner-friendly sections)\n4. \"Programming C#\" by Ian Griffiths\n\nIntermediate Level:\n1. \"Pro C# 10 with .NET 6\" by Andrew Troelsen and Philip Japikse\n2. \"C# in Depth\" by Jon Skeet\n3. \"Dependency Injection in .NET\" by Mark Seemann\n4. \"Microservices in .NET\" by Christian Horsdal Gammelgaard\n\nAdvanced Level:\n1. \"Elegant Code: Software Design Principles\" by Mark Seemann\n2. \"CLR via C#\" by Jeffrey Richter\n3. \"Functional Programming in C#\" by Enrico Buonanno\n4. \"Design Patterns in C#\" by Gang of Four adaptation\n\nOnline Resources:\n- Microsoft Learn\n- YouTube tutorials\n- Pluralsight courses\n- Udemy C# courses\n\nThese books cover various aspects from basic syntax to advanced design patterns and architectural principles.",
